## 5. Performance Optimization

### GC Avoidance (Critical for 60fps)

The main performance bottleneck in JavaScript WebGL applications is **Garbage Collection**, not rendering.

**Why GC is problematic:**
- GC timing is unpredictable
- Can cause frame drops and stuttering
- No direct control over when it runs

**Source:** [Wonderland Engine - WebGL Performance](https://wonderlandengine.com/about/webgl-performance/)

### Object Pooling Pattern

```typescript
// Object pool for reusing temporary objects
class ObjectPool<T> {
  private pool: T[] = [];
  private factory: () => T;

  constructor(factory: () => T, initialSize: number = 10) {
    this.factory = factory;
    for (let i = 0; i < initialSize; i++) {
      this.pool.push(factory());
    }
  }

  acquire(): T {
    return this.pool.pop() || this.factory();
  }

  release(obj: T): void {
    this.pool.push(obj);
  }
}

// Usage for Three.js vectors/matrices
const vector3Pool = new ObjectPool(() => new THREE.Vector3(), 50);
const matrix4Pool = new ObjectPool(() => new THREE.Matrix4(), 50);

// In animation loop
function update() {
  const temp = vector3Pool.acquire();
  temp.set(x, y, z);
  // ... use temp ...
  vector3Pool.release(temp);
}
```

### TypedArrays and Memory

```typescript
// Use TypedArrays for large data sets
const positions = new Float32Array(count * 3);
const colors = new Uint8Array(count * 4);

// Benefits:
// - Contiguous memory allocation
// - No GC for individual elements
// - Direct GPU upload
// - Cache-friendly iteration
```

**Source:** [MDN - WebGL Best Practices](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/WebGL_API/WebGL_best_practices)

### useFrame Best Practices (R3F)

```typescript
// BAD: Creates garbage every frame
useFrame(() => {
  ref.current.position.lerp(new THREE.Vector3(x, y, z), 0.1);
});

// GOOD: Reuse objects
const targetRef = useRef(new THREE.Vector3());
useFrame((state, delta) => {
  targetRef.current.set(x, y, z);
  ref.current.position.lerp(targetRef.current, delta * 5);
});
```

**Source:** [R3F Performance Pitfalls](https://r3f.docs.pmnd.rs/advanced/pitfalls)

### Frame Budget Analysis

**Target:** 60fps = 16.67ms per frame

| Operation | Budget | Priority |
|-----------|--------|----------|
| Render (GPU) | ~8ms | Critical |
| JavaScript | ~5ms | Critical |
| Layout/Paint | ~2ms | Low |
| GC | 0ms target | Eliminate |

### Structure of Arrays (SoA) Pattern

**AoS (Array of Structs):** Traditional object-oriented pattern
```typescript
// Bad for performance with large datasets
const tasks = [
  { x: 0, y: 0, width: 10, color: 'blue' },
  { x: 10, y: 0, width: 5, color: 'red' }
];
```

**SoA (Struct of Arrays):** Cache-friendly pattern
```typescript
// Good for batch processing
const taskData = {
  x: new Float32Array([0, 10, ...]),
  y: new Float32Array([0, 0, ...]),
  width: new Float32Array([10, 5, ...]),
  color: new Uint8Array([0, 1, ...]) // Color index
};
```

**Performance impact:** 10-100x improvement for batch operations due to:
- Better CPU cache utilization
- SIMD vectorization opportunities
- GPU memory coalescing

**Source:** [SoA vs AoS Performance](https://lobste.rs/s/gs5ujg/why_object_arrays_soa_pattern_beat)

### WebGL Draw Call Optimization

**Batching rules:**
- Target < 1000 draw calls
- Use instancing for repeated geometry
- Use texture atlases for multiple textures
- Use `WEBGL_multi_draw` extension when available

**Source:** [MDN - WebGL Best Practices](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/WebGL_API/WebGL_best_practices)

